#: ../../../user-guide.rst:2
msgid "User Guide"
msgstr "使用者指南"

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:7
msgid "Installing"
msgstr "安裝方式"

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:9
msgid "urllib3 can be installed with `pip <https://pip.pypa.io>`_"
msgstr "urllib3 可以透過 `pip <https://pip.pypa.io>`_ 進行安裝"

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:11
msgid "$ python -m pip install urllib3"
msgstr "$ python -m pip install urllib3"

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:17
msgid "Making Requests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:19
msgid "First things first, import the urllib3 module:"
msgstr "首先，匯入 urllib3 模組："

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:21
msgid ">>> import urllib3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:25
msgid ""
"You'll need a :class:`~poolmanager.PoolManager` instance to make requests. "
"This object handles all of the details of connection pooling and thread "
"safety so that you don't have to:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:29
msgid ">>> http = urllib3.PoolManager()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:33
msgid "To make a request use :meth:`~poolmanager.PoolManager.request`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:35
msgid ""
">>> r = http.request('GET', 'http://httpbin.org/robots.txt')\n"
">>> r.data\n"
"b'User-agent: *\\nDisallow: /deny\\n'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:41
msgid ""
"``request()`` returns a :class:`~response.HTTPResponse` object, the :ref:"
"`response_content` section explains how to handle various responses."
msgstr ""
"``request()`` 會回傳一個 :class:`~response.HTTPResponse` 物件，:ref:"
"`response_content` 小節解釋了如何處理各種回應。"

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:44
msgid ""
"You can use :meth:`~poolmanager.PoolManager.request` to make requests using "
"any HTTP verb:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:47
msgid ""
">>> r = http.request(\n"
"...     'POST',\n"
"...     'http://httpbin.org/post',\n"
"...     fields={'hello': 'world'}\n"
"... )"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:55
msgid ""
"The :ref:`request_data` section covers sending other kinds of requests data, "
"including JSON, files, and binary data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:61
msgid "Response Content"
msgstr "回應內容"

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:63
msgid ""
"The :class:`~response.HTTPResponse` object provides :attr:`~response."
"HTTPResponse.status`, :attr:`~response.HTTPResponse.data`, and :attr:"
"`~response.HTTPResponse.headers` attributes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:67
msgid ""
">>> r = http.request('GET', 'http://httpbin.org/ip')\n"
">>> r.status\n"
"200\n"
">>> r.data\n"
"b'{\\n  \"origin\": \"104.232.115.37\"\\n}\\n'\n"
">>> r.headers\n"
"HTTPHeaderDict({'Content-Length': '33', ...})"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:78
msgid "JSON Content"
msgstr "JSON 內容"

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:80
msgid ""
"JSON content can be loaded by decoding and deserializing the :attr:"
"`~response.HTTPResponse.data` attribute of the request:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:83
msgid ""
">>> import json\n"
">>> r = http.request('GET', 'http://httpbin.org/ip')\n"
">>> json.loads(r.data.decode('utf-8'))\n"
"{'origin': '127.0.0.1'}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:91
msgid "Binary Content"
msgstr "二進位內容"

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:93
msgid ""
"The :attr:`~response.HTTPResponse.data` attribute of the response is always "
"set to a byte string representing the response content:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:96
msgid ""
">>> r = http.request('GET', 'http://httpbin.org/bytes/8')\n"
">>> r.data\n"
"b'\\xaa\\xa5H?\\x95\\xe9\\x9b\\x11'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:102
msgid ""
"For larger responses, it's sometimes better to :ref:`stream <stream>` the "
"response."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:106
msgid "Using io Wrappers with Response Content"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:108
msgid ""
"Sometimes you want to use :class:`io.TextIOWrapper` or similar objects like "
"a CSV reader directly with :class:`~response.HTTPResponse` data. Making "
"these two interfaces play nice together requires using the :attr:`~response."
"HTTPResponse.auto_close` attribute by setting it to ``False``. By default "
"HTTP responses are closed after reading all bytes, this disables that "
"behavior:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:113
msgid ""
">>> import io\n"
">>> r = http.request('GET', 'https://example.com', preload_content=False)\n"
">>> r.auto_close = False\n"
">>> for line in io.TextIOWrapper(r):\n"
">>>     print(line)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:124
msgid "Request Data"
msgstr "請求資料"

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:127
msgid "Headers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:129
msgid ""
"You can specify headers as a dictionary in the ``headers`` argument in :meth:"
"`~poolmanager.PoolManager.request`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:131
msgid ""
">>> r = http.request(\n"
"...     'GET',\n"
"...     'http://httpbin.org/headers',\n"
"...     headers={\n"
"...         'X-Something': 'value'\n"
"...     }\n"
"... )\n"
">>> json.loads(r.data.decode('utf-8'))['headers']\n"
"{'X-Something': 'value', ...}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:144
msgid "Query Parameters"
msgstr "查詢參數"

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:146
msgid ""
"For ``GET``, ``HEAD``, and ``DELETE`` requests, you can simply pass the "
"arguments as a dictionary in the ``fields`` argument to :meth:`~poolmanager."
"PoolManager.request`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:150
msgid ""
">>> r = http.request(\n"
"...     'GET',\n"
"...     'http://httpbin.org/get',\n"
"...     fields={'arg': 'value'}\n"
"... )\n"
">>> json.loads(r.data.decode('utf-8'))['args']\n"
"{'arg': 'value'}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:160
msgid ""
"For ``POST`` and ``PUT`` requests, you need to manually encode query "
"parameters in the URL:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:163
msgid ""
">>> from urllib.parse import urlencode\n"
">>> encoded_args = urlencode({'arg': 'value'})\n"
">>> url = 'http://httpbin.org/post?' + encoded_args\n"
">>> r = http.request('POST', url)\n"
">>> json.loads(r.data.decode('utf-8'))['args']\n"
"{'arg': 'value'}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:176
msgid "Form Data"
msgstr "標單資料"

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:178
msgid ""
"For ``PUT`` and ``POST`` requests, urllib3 will automatically form-encode "
"the dictionary in the ``fields`` argument provided to :meth:`~poolmanager."
"PoolManager.request`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:182
msgid ""
">>> r = http.request(\n"
"...     'POST',\n"
"...     'http://httpbin.org/post',\n"
"...     fields={'field': 'value'}\n"
"... )\n"
">>> json.loads(r.data.decode('utf-8'))['form']\n"
"{'field': 'value'}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:193
msgid "JSON"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:195
msgid ""
"You can send a JSON request by specifying the encoded data as the ``body`` "
"argument and setting the ``Content-Type`` header when calling :meth:"
"`~poolmanager.PoolManager.request`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:199
msgid ""
">>> import json\n"
">>> data = {'attribute': 'value'}\n"
">>> encoded_data = json.dumps(data).encode('utf-8')\n"
">>> r = http.request(\n"
"...     'POST',\n"
"...     'http://httpbin.org/post',\n"
"...     body=encoded_data,\n"
"...     headers={'Content-Type': 'application/json'}\n"
"... )\n"
">>> json.loads(r.data.decode('utf-8'))['json']\n"
"{'attribute': 'value'}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:214
msgid "Files & Binary Data"
msgstr "檔案與二進位資料"

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:216
msgid ""
"For uploading files using ``multipart/form-data`` encoding you can use the "
"same approach as :ref:`form_data` and specify the file field as a tuple of "
"``(file_name, file_data)``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:220
msgid ""
">>> with open('example.txt') as fp:\n"
"...     file_data = fp.read()\n"
">>> r = http.request(\n"
"...     'POST',\n"
"...     'http://httpbin.org/post',\n"
"...     fields={\n"
"...         'filefield': ('example.txt', file_data),\n"
"...     }\n"
"... )\n"
">>> json.loads(r.data.decode('utf-8'))['files']\n"
"{'filefield': '...'}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:234
msgid ""
"While specifying the filename is not strictly required, it's recommended in "
"order to match browser behavior. You can also pass a third item in the tuple "
"to specify the file's MIME type explicitly:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:238
msgid ""
">>> r = http.request(\n"
"...     'POST',\n"
"...     'http://httpbin.org/post',\n"
"...     fields={\n"
"...         'filefield': ('example.txt', file_data, 'text/plain'),\n"
"...     }\n"
"... )"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:248
msgid ""
"For sending raw binary data simply specify the ``body`` argument. It's also "
"recommended to set the ``Content-Type`` header:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:251
msgid ""
">>> with open('example.jpg', 'rb') as fp:\n"
"...     binary_data = fp.read()\n"
">>> r = http.request(\n"
"...     'POST',\n"
"...     'http://httpbin.org/post',\n"
"...     body=binary_data,\n"
"...     headers={'Content-Type': 'image/jpeg'}\n"
"... )\n"
">>> json.loads(r.data.decode('utf-8'))['data']\n"
"b'...'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:267
msgid "Certificate Verification"
msgstr "證書驗證"

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:269
msgid "*New in version 1.25:*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:271
msgid ""
"HTTPS connections are now verified by default (``cert_reqs = "
"'CERT_REQUIRED'``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:273
msgid ""
"While you can disable certification verification by setting ``cert_reqs = "
"'CERT_NONE'``, it is highly recommend to leave it on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:275
msgid ""
"Unless otherwise specified urllib3 will try to load the default system "
"certificate stores. The most reliable cross-platform method is to use the "
"`certifi <https://certifi.io/>`_ package which provides Mozilla's root "
"certificate bundle:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:279
msgid "$ python -m pip install certifi"
msgstr "$ python -m pip install certifi"

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:283
msgid ""
"You can also install certifi along with urllib3 by using the ``secure`` "
"extra:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:286 ../../../user-guide.rst:332
msgid "$ python -m pip install urllib3[secure]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:290
msgid ""
"If you're using Python 2 you may need additional packages. See the :ref:"
"`section below <ssl_py2>` for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:292
msgid ""
"Once you have certificates, you can create a :class:`~poolmanager."
"PoolManager` that verifies certificates when making requests:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:295 ../../../user-guide.rst:355
msgid ""
">>> import certifi\n"
">>> import urllib3\n"
">>> http = urllib3.PoolManager(\n"
"...     cert_reqs='CERT_REQUIRED',\n"
"...     ca_certs=certifi.where()\n"
"... )"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:304
msgid ""
"The :class:`~poolmanager.PoolManager` will automatically handle certificate "
"verification and will raise :class:`~exceptions.SSLError` if verification "
"fails:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:307
msgid ""
">>> http.request('GET', 'https://google.com')\n"
"(No exception)\n"
">>> http.request('GET', 'https://expired.badssl.com')\n"
"urllib3.exceptions.SSLError ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:314
msgid ""
"You can use OS-provided certificates if desired. Just specify the full path "
"to the certificate bundle as the ``ca_certs`` argument instead of ``certifi."
"where()``. For example, most Linux systems store the certificates at ``/etc/"
"ssl/certs/ca-certificates.crt``. Other operating systems can be `difficult "
"<https://stackoverflow.com/questions/10095676/openssl-reasonable-default-for-"
"trusted-ca-certificates>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:323
msgid "Certificate Verification in Python 2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:325
msgid ""
"Older versions of Python 2 are built with an :mod:`ssl` module that lacks :"
"ref:`SNI support <sni_warning>` and can lag behind security updates. For "
"these reasons it's recommended to use `pyOpenSSL <https://pyopenssl."
"readthedocs.io/en/latest/>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:329
msgid ""
"If you install urllib3 with the ``secure`` extra, all required packages for "
"certificate verification on Python 2 will be installed:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:336
msgid ""
"If you want to install the packages manually, you will need ``pyOpenSSL``, "
"``cryptography``, ``idna``, and ``certifi``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:339
msgid ""
"If you are not using macOS or Windows, note that `cryptography <https://"
"cryptography.io/en/latest/>`_ requires additional system packages to "
"compile. See `building cryptography on Linux <https://cryptography.io/en/"
"latest/installation/#building-cryptography-on-linux>`_ for the list of "
"packages required."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:345
msgid ""
"Once installed, you can tell urllib3 to use pyOpenSSL by using :mod:`urllib3."
"contrib.pyopenssl`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:347
msgid ""
">>> import urllib3.contrib.pyopenssl\n"
">>> urllib3.contrib.pyopenssl.inject_into_urllib3()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:352
msgid ""
"Finally, you can create a :class:`~poolmanager.PoolManager` that verifies "
"certificates when performing requests:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:364
msgid ""
"If you do not wish to use pyOpenSSL, you can simply omit the call to :func:"
"`urllib3.contrib.pyopenssl.inject_into_urllib3`. urllib3 will fall back to "
"the standard-library :mod:`ssl` module. You may experience :ref:`several "
"warnings <ssl_warnings>` when doing this."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:369
msgid ""
"If you do not use pyOpenSSL, Python must be compiled with ssl support for "
"certificate verification to work. It is uncommon, but it is possible to "
"compile Python without SSL support. See this `StackOverflow thread <https://"
"stackoverflow.com/questions/5128845/importerror-no-module-named-ssl>`_ for "
"more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:375
msgid ""
"If you are on Google App Engine, you must explicitly enable SSL support in "
"your ``app.yaml``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:378
msgid ""
"libraries:\n"
"- name: ssl\n"
"  version: latest"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:385
msgid "Using Timeouts"
msgstr "使用逾時"

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:387
msgid ""
"Timeouts allow you to control how long (in seconds) requests are allowed to "
"run before being aborted. In simple cases, you can specify a timeout as a "
"``float`` to :meth:`~poolmanager.PoolManager.request`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:391
msgid ""
">>> http.request(\n"
"...     'GET', 'http://httpbin.org/delay/3', timeout=4.0\n"
"... )\n"
"<urllib3.response.HTTPResponse>\n"
">>> http.request(\n"
"...     'GET', 'http://httpbin.org/delay/3', timeout=2.5\n"
"... )\n"
"MaxRetryError caused by ReadTimeoutError"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:402
msgid ""
"For more granular control you can use a :class:`~util.timeout.Timeout` "
"instance which lets you specify separate connect and read timeouts:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:405
msgid ""
">>> http.request(\n"
"...     'GET',\n"
"...     'http://httpbin.org/delay/3',\n"
"...     timeout=urllib3.Timeout(connect=1.0)\n"
"... )\n"
"<urllib3.response.HTTPResponse>\n"
">>> http.request(\n"
"...     'GET',\n"
"...     'http://httpbin.org/delay/3',\n"
"...     timeout=urllib3.Timeout(connect=1.0, read=2.0)\n"
"... )\n"
"MaxRetryError caused by ReadTimeoutError"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:421
msgid ""
"If you want all requests to be subject to the same timeout, you can specify "
"the timeout at the :class:`~urllib3.poolmanager.PoolManager` level:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:424
msgid ""
">>> http = urllib3.PoolManager(timeout=3.0)\n"
">>> http = urllib3.PoolManager(\n"
"...     timeout=urllib3.Timeout(connect=1.0, read=2.0)\n"
"... )"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:431
msgid ""
"You still override this pool-level timeout by specifying ``timeout`` to :"
"meth:`~poolmanager.PoolManager.request`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:435
msgid "Retrying Requests"
msgstr "重試請求"

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:437
msgid ""
"urllib3 can automatically retry idempotent requests. This same mechanism "
"also handles redirects. You can control the retries using the ``retries`` "
"parameter to :meth:`~poolmanager.PoolManager.request`. By default, urllib3 "
"will retry requests 3 times and follow up to 3 redirects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:442
msgid "To change the number of retries just specify an integer:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:444
msgid ">>> http.requests('GET', 'http://httpbin.org/ip', retries=10)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:448
msgid "To disable all retry and redirect logic specify ``retries=False``:"
msgstr "若要停用所有重試和重新導向邏輯，請指定 ``retries=False``："

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:450
msgid ""
">>> http.request(\n"
"...     'GET', 'http://nxdomain.example.com', retries=False\n"
"... )\n"
"NewConnectionError\n"
">>> r = http.request(\n"
"...     'GET', 'http://httpbin.org/redirect/1', retries=False\n"
"... )\n"
">>> r.status\n"
"302"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:462
msgid ""
"To disable redirects but keep the retrying logic, specify ``redirect=False``:"
msgstr "若要停用重新導向但保留重試邏輯，請指定 ``redirect=False``："

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:464
msgid ""
">>> r = http.request(\n"
"...     'GET', 'http://httpbin.org/redirect/1', redirect=False\n"
"... )\n"
">>> r.status\n"
"302"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:472
msgid ""
"For more granular control you can use a :class:`~util.retry.Retry` instance. "
"This class allows you far greater control of how requests are retried."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:475
msgid "For example, to do a total of 3 retries, but limit to only 2 redirects:"
msgstr "例如，若要進行總共 3 次重試，但限制最多僅能有 2 次重新導向："

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:477
msgid ""
">>> http.request(\n"
"...     'GET',\n"
"...     'http://httpbin.org/redirect/3',\n"
"...     retries=urllib3.Retry(3, redirect=2)\n"
"... )\n"
"MaxRetryError"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:486
msgid ""
"You can also disable exceptions for too many redirects and just return the "
"``302`` response:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:489
msgid ""
">>> r = http.request(\n"
"...     'GET',\n"
"...     'http://httpbin.org/redirect/3',\n"
"...     retries=urllib3.Retry(\n"
"...         redirect=2, raise_on_redirect=False)\n"
"... )\n"
">>> r.status\n"
"302"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:500
msgid ""
"If you want all requests to be subject to the same retry policy, you can "
"specify the retry at the :class:`~urllib3.poolmanager.PoolManager` level:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:503
msgid ""
">>> http = urllib3.PoolManager(retries=False)\n"
">>> http = urllib3.PoolManager(\n"
"...     retries=urllib3.Retry(5, redirect=2)\n"
"... )"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:510
msgid ""
"You still override this pool-level retry policy by specifying ``retries`` "
"to :meth:`~poolmanager.PoolManager.request`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:514
msgid "Errors & Exceptions"
msgstr "錯誤與例外"

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:516
msgid "urllib3 wraps lower-level exceptions, for example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:518
msgid ""
">>> try:\n"
"...     http.request('GET', 'nx.example.com', retries=False)\n"
"... except urllib3.exceptions.NewConnectionError:\n"
"...     print('Connection failed.')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:525
msgid "See :mod:`~urllib3.exceptions` for the full list of all exceptions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:528
msgid "Logging"
msgstr "日誌紀錄"

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:530
msgid ""
"If you are using the standard library :mod:`logging` module urllib3 will "
"emit several logs. In some cases this can be undesirable. You can use the "
"standard logger interface to change the log level for urllib3's logger:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user-guide.rst:534
msgid ">>> logging.getLogger(\"urllib3\").setLevel(logging.WARNING)"
msgstr ""
